            <content:encoded><![CDATA[https://kotaku.com/tips-for-monster-hunter-wilds-the-first-berserker-dyn-1851776809<br/><br/><div id="readability-page-1" class="page"><div><div><figure id="" data-id="8d37c14b6ffe93c32d85ee4b5c5253c4" data-recommend-id="image://8d37c14b6ffe93c32d85ee4b5c5253c4" data-format="jpg" data-width="1280" data-height="720" data-lightbox="false" data-recommended="false" data-hide="false" contenteditable="false" draggable="false"><div contenteditable="false" data-link-reference="" data-link-target="" data-syndicationrights="false" data-imagerights="in-house-art" data-hide="false" data-hidecredit="false"><p><figcaption>Screenshot<!-- -->: <!-- -->Capcom / Samuel Moreno / Kotaku<!-- -->, <!-- -->Capcom / Samuel Moreno / Kotaku<!-- -->, <!-- -->Neople / Billy Givens / Kotaku<!-- -->, <!-- -->Supergiant Games / Kotaku<!-- -->, <!-- -->Koei Tecmo Games / Timothy Monbleau / Kotaku<!-- -->, <!-- -->Neople / Billy Givens / Kotaku<!-- -->, <!-- -->Image<!-- -->: <!-- -->Blizzard Entertainment / Samuel Moreno / Kotaku</figcaption></p></div><span data-id="8d37c14b6ffe93c32d85ee4b5c5253c4" data-recommend-id="image://8d37c14b6ffe93c32d85ee4b5c5253c4" data-format="jpg" data-width="1280" data-height="720" data-lightbox="false" data-recommended="false" data-hide="false"></span></figure><p>This week we’ve got plenty of <em>Monster Hunter Wilds </em>tips for ya on everything from mastering the cool Stalwart Guard technique to snagging some great items that can give you an edge. We’ll also guide you to some great armor in <em>The First Berserker </em>that will let you stay cool under pressure, and give you some pointers for leveling up fast in <em>Dynasty Warriors: Origins</em>. </p></div><div><figure id="" data-id="3979bb9633d82d897bead95f3f983a83" data-recommend-id="image://3979bb9633d82d897bead95f3f983a83" data-format="jpg" data-width="1920" data-height="1079" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="A knight stands on a bridge with a castle in the background in a game with somewhat old-school 3D graphics." data-recommended="false" data-hide="false" contenteditable="false" draggable="false"><div contenteditable="false" data-alt="A knight stands on a bridge with a castle in the background in a game with somewhat old-school 3D graphics." data-link-reference="" data-link-target="" data-syndicationrights="false" data-imagerights="other-license" data-hide="false" data-hidecredit="false"><p><figcaption>Screenshot<!-- -->: <!-- -->Burgee Media / Kotaku</figcaption></p></div><span data-id="3979bb9633d82d897bead95f3f983a83" data-recommend-id="image://3979bb9633d82d897bead95f3f983a83" data-format="jpg" data-width="1920" data-height="1079" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="A knight stands on a bridge with a castle in the background in a game with somewhat old-school 3D graphics." data-recommended="false" data-hide="false"></span></figure><p>At first glance, a single-player MMORPG doesn’t make a ton of sense. But in practice, it’s an exciting prospect, a world filled with simulated players, grinding mobs, completing quests, and sharing barbed words in global chat—and none of them are real people. It’s also a decent way to get try out the MMO experience as a solo player if you’ve avoided the genre previously.  - Brandon Morgan <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/erenshor-single-player-mmorpg-steam-dungeon-party-guild-1851776313&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/erenshor-single-player-mmorpg-steam-dungeon-party-guild-1851776313">Read More</a></span></p></div><div><figure id="" data-id="98db53f29b2d6339e3f84a4a4f5ceeec" data-recommend-id="image://98db53f29b2d6339e3f84a4a4f5ceeec" data-format="gif" data-width="800" data-height="450" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="A hunter blocks a monster's fire attack by moving forward with a large shield." data-recommended="false" data-hide="false" contenteditable="false" draggable="false"><div contenteditable="false" data-alt="A hunter blocks a monster's fire attack by moving forward with a large shield." data-link-reference="" data-link-target="" data-syndicationrights="true" data-imagerights="fair-use" data-hide="false" data-hidecredit="false"><p><figcaption>Gif<!-- -->: <!-- -->Capcom / Samuel Moreno / Kotaku</figcaption></p></div><span data-id="98db53f29b2d6339e3f84a4a4f5ceeec" data-recommend-id="image://98db53f29b2d6339e3f84a4a4f5ceeec" data-format="gif" data-width="800" data-height="450" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="A hunter blocks a monster's fire attack by moving forward with a large shield." data-recommended="false" data-hide="false"></span></figure><p>Although there are a lot of <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/monster-hunter-wilds-wounds-hunter-mode-solo-co-op-1851771276&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/monster-hunter-wilds-wounds-hunter-mode-solo-co-op-1851771276">new mechanics</a></span> that <em>Monster Hunter Wilds</em> puts front and center, quite a few are specific to certain weapons. Stalwart Guard is one such mechanic. And unfortunately there’s no real in-game explanation for how it works. - Samuel Moreno <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/monster-hunter-wilds-stalwart-guard-weapons-defend-1851776632&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/monster-hunter-wilds-stalwart-guard-weapons-defend-1851776632">Read More</a></span></p></div><div><figure id="" data-id="cc3c852c6b8b200632edc5a8f1c89ccf" data-recommend-id="image://cc3c852c6b8b200632edc5a8f1c89ccf" data-format="jpg" data-width="1920" data-height="1080" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="An Ajarakan throws a flaming rock at a Hunter within Wounded Hollow." data-recommended="false" data-hide="false" contenteditable="false" draggable="false"><div contenteditable="false" data-alt="An Ajarakan throws a flaming rock at a Hunter within Wounded Hollow." data-link-reference="" data-link-target="" data-syndicationrights="true" data-imagerights="fair-use" data-hide="false" data-hidecredit="false"><p><figcaption>Screenshot<!-- -->: <!-- -->Capcom / Samuel Moreno / Kotaku</figcaption></p></div><span data-id="cc3c852c6b8b200632edc5a8f1c89ccf" data-recommend-id="image://cc3c852c6b8b200632edc5a8f1c89ccf" data-format="jpg" data-width="1920" data-height="1080" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="An Ajarakan throws a flaming rock at a Hunter within Wounded Hollow." data-recommended="false" data-hide="false"></span></figure><p>Although <em>Monster Hunter Wilds</em> has a ton of new features and mechanics, you’ll still use the same iconic weapons to take down monsters and craft <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/monster-hunter-wilds-appearance-cosmetics-transmog-1851772498&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/monster-hunter-wilds-appearance-cosmetics-transmog-1851772498">cool-looking armor</a></span>. The always-helpful Armorcharm and Powercharm have also returned, but they’re easy to miss this time around. You’ll want to get these as soon as possible to have that extra edge for tough hunts. - Samuel Moreno <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/monster-hunter-wilds-armorcharm-powercharm-location-1851776278&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/monster-hunter-wilds-armorcharm-powercharm-location-1851776278">Read More</a></span></p></div><div><figure id="" data-id="e50b4bf12937d032d37b710eac7568c2" data-recommend-id="image://e50b4bf12937d032d37b710eac7568c2" data-format="jpg" data-width="1920" data-height="1080" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="The hunter sits wide awake while her palico blissfully naps." data-recommended="false" data-hide="false" contenteditable="false" draggable="false"><div contenteditable="false" data-alt="The hunter sits wide awake while her palico blissfully naps." data-link-reference="" data-link-target="" data-syndicationrights="true" data-imagerights="fair-use" data-hide="false" data-hidecredit="false"><p><figcaption>Screenshot<!-- -->: <!-- -->Capcom / Samuel Moreno / Kotaku</figcaption></p></div><span data-id="e50b4bf12937d032d37b710eac7568c2" data-recommend-id="image://e50b4bf12937d032d37b710eac7568c2" data-format="jpg" data-width="1920" data-height="1080" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="The hunter sits wide awake while her palico blissfully naps." data-recommended="false" data-hide="false"></span></figure><p><em>Monster Hunter Wilds</em> has brought a ton of new features along for the latest entry in the series. While both the <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/monster-hunter-wilds-wounds-hunter-mode-solo-co-op-1851771276&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/monster-hunter-wilds-wounds-hunter-mode-solo-co-op-1851771276">Wounds System</a></span> and <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/monster-hunter-wilds-power-clash-explained-guarding-1851775741&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/monster-hunter-wilds-power-clash-explained-guarding-1851775741">Power Clash</a></span> mechanics are vital for combat, equally exciting is the addition of a Day/Night cycle, complete with weather events. Naturally, there is also a Rest feature to let you change the time of day—but it comes with some cryptically important limitations. Understanding your way around this will be crucial when you’re trying to hunt specific monsters. - Samuel Moreno <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/monster-hunter-wilds-rest-plenty-fallow-inclemency-1851776094&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/monster-hunter-wilds-rest-plenty-fallow-inclemency-1851776094">Read More</a></span></p></div><div><figure id="" data-id="9eac8e49223ded188c99a9b326e829c2" data-recommend-id="image://9eac8e49223ded188c99a9b326e829c2" data-format="jpg" data-width="1920" data-height="1080" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="An armored NPC stands before the camera." data-recommended="false" data-hide="false" contenteditable="false" draggable="false"><div contenteditable="false" data-alt="An armored NPC stands before the camera." data-link-reference="" data-link-target="" data-syndicationrights="true" data-imagerights="fair-use" data-hide="false" data-hidecredit="false"><p><figcaption>Screenshot<!-- -->: <!-- -->Neople / Billy Givens / Kotaku</figcaption></p></div><span data-id="9eac8e49223ded188c99a9b326e829c2" data-recommend-id="image://9eac8e49223ded188c99a9b326e829c2" data-format="jpg" data-width="1920" data-height="1080" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="An armored NPC stands before the camera." data-recommended="false" data-hide="false"></span></figure><p>New Game Plus is a staple of the soulslike genre. So it shouldn’t come as a surprise that <em>The First Berserker: Khazan</em> provides this option after finishing its campaign for the first time. If you want to know how this popular feature works in this challenging adventure, read on to learn how to start New Game Plus and to know what’s different in your second playthrough and beyond. - Billy Givens <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/first-berserker-khazan-new-game-plus-legendary-transmog-1851776611&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/first-berserker-khazan-new-game-plus-legendary-transmog-1851776611">Read More</a></span></p></div><div><figure id="" data-id="be0541b7e5774b4b097485becdab561b" data-recommend-id="image://be0541b7e5774b4b097485becdab561b" data-format="jpg" data-width="1920" data-height="1080" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="Typhon stares down the player in Hades 2." data-recommended="false" data-hide="false" contenteditable="false" draggable="false"><div contenteditable="false" data-alt="Typhon stares down the player in Hades 2." data-link-reference="" data-link-target="" data-syndicationrights="true" data-imagerights="fair-use" data-hide="false" data-hidecredit="false"><p><figcaption>Screenshot<!-- -->: <!-- -->Supergiant Games / Kotaku</figcaption></p></div><span data-id="be0541b7e5774b4b097485becdab561b" data-recommend-id="image://be0541b7e5774b4b097485becdab561b" data-format="jpg" data-width="1920" data-height="1080" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="Typhon stares down the player in Hades 2." data-recommended="false" data-hide="false"></span></figure><p>If you’re coming back to <em>Hades 2</em> after some time away, you’ll be pleased to find the game received a generous update that, among other cool additions, tossed in a new boss: Typhon, Father of All Monsters.  - Parker Johnson <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/hades-2-typhon-boss-eggs-tornado-keepsake-health-bar-1851776071&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/hades-2-typhon-boss-eggs-tornado-keepsake-health-bar-1851776071">Read More</a></span></p></div><div><figure id="" data-id="9f06841db9bc6221f005705a92ee7e90" data-recommend-id="image://9f06841db9bc6221f005705a92ee7e90" data-format="jpg" data-width="2048" data-height="1152" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="A screenshot from Dynasty Warriors: Origins. The protagonist is facing the camera and glancing to the side." data-recommended="false" data-hide="false" contenteditable="false" draggable="false"><div contenteditable="false" data-alt="A screenshot from Dynasty Warriors: Origins. The protagonist is facing the camera and glancing to the side." data-link-reference="" data-link-target="" data-syndicationrights="true" data-imagerights="fair-use" data-hide="false" data-hidecredit="false"><p><figcaption>Screenshot<!-- -->: <!-- -->Koei Tecmo Games / Timothy Monbleau / Kotaku</figcaption></p></div><span data-id="9f06841db9bc6221f005705a92ee7e90" data-recommend-id="image://9f06841db9bc6221f005705a92ee7e90" data-format="jpg" data-width="2048" data-height="1152" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="A screenshot from Dynasty Warriors: Origins. The protagonist is facing the camera and glancing to the side." data-recommended="false" data-hide="false"></span></figure><p><em>Dynasty Warriors: Origins </em>is nothing if not a power fantasy. Fighting thousands of grunts at once is fun in and of itself, but soaking up loads of skill points and experience points to unlock consistently stronger abilities makes the game hard to put down. That said, while <em>Origins </em>isn’t necessarily complex, its leveling system is idiosyncratic enough that I had to use the word idiosyncratic to describe it. This was always how I imagined I’d use my English degree. - Timothy Monbleau <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/dynasty-warriors-origins-level-up-weapons-difficulty-1851776109&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/dynasty-warriors-origins-level-up-weapons-difficulty-1851776109">Read More</a></span></p></div><div><figure id="" data-id="99b87b12d38a2a3a08644bcd9e024680" data-recommend-id="image://99b87b12d38a2a3a08644bcd9e024680" data-format="jpg" data-width="1920" data-height="1080" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="The protagonist of The First Berserker wears dragon-themed armor while standing on a bridge." data-recommended="false" data-hide="false" contenteditable="false" draggable="false"><div contenteditable="false" data-alt="The protagonist of The First Berserker wears dragon-themed armor while standing on a bridge." data-link-reference="" data-link-target="" data-syndicationrights="true" data-imagerights="fair-use" data-hide="false" data-hidecredit="false"><p><figcaption>Screenshot<!-- -->: <!-- -->Neople / Billy Givens / Kotaku</figcaption></p></div><span data-id="99b87b12d38a2a3a08644bcd9e024680" data-recommend-id="image://99b87b12d38a2a3a08644bcd9e024680" data-format="jpg" data-width="1920" data-height="1080" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="The protagonist of The First Berserker wears dragon-themed armor while standing on a bridge." data-recommended="false" data-hide="false"></span></figure><p><em>The First Berserker: Khazan</em> features plenty of fashionable and functional armor, including the very <em>Skyrim</em>-esque Dragonknight Set, which most certainly lives up to its dragon-focused name. But getting the ability to craft this armor requires you to first find the Dragonknight’s Scroll, which isn’t available until the back half of the game. But don’t worry, we’ll fill you in on what to know about the Dragonknight Set and where to find the Dragonknight’s Scroll. - Billy Givens <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/first-berserker-khazan-fire-resistance-armor-set-scroll-1851776411&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/first-berserker-khazan-fire-resistance-armor-set-scroll-1851776411">Read More</a></span></p></div><div><figure id="" data-id="d71c6b2b7bb8f01c866b31093c36e9e7" data-recommend-id="image://d71c6b2b7bb8f01c866b31093c36e9e7" data-format="jpg" data-width="1920" data-height="1080" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="Ana swings her sleep dart gun behind her during a highlight intro." data-recommended="false" data-hide="false" contenteditable="false" draggable="false"><div contenteditable="false" data-alt="Ana swings her sleep dart gun behind her during a highlight intro." data-link-reference="" data-link-target="" data-syndicationrights="false" data-imagerights="other-license" data-hide="false" data-hidecredit="false"><p><figcaption>Image<!-- -->: <!-- -->Blizzard Entertainment / Samuel Moreno / Kotaku</figcaption></p></div><span data-id="d71c6b2b7bb8f01c866b31093c36e9e7" data-recommend-id="image://d71c6b2b7bb8f01c866b31093c36e9e7" data-format="jpg" data-width="1920" data-height="1080" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="Ana swings her sleep dart gun behind her during a highlight intro." data-recommended="false" data-hide="false"></span></figure><p>As exciting as the return of <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/overwatch-2-loot-boxes-season-15-skins-cosmetics-1851762971&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/overwatch-2-loot-boxes-season-15-skins-cosmetics-1851762971">Loot Boxes</a></span> is, the biggest change for <em>Overwatch 2</em> is season 15’s perk system. Whether they’re small tweaks for healing or new mobility options, healers need to choose the right upgrades. To make that a bit easier, we’ve narrowed down the best perk choices for each Support hero so you can keep your team alive. - Samuel Moreno <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/overwatch-support-perk-mercy-kiriko-juno-zenyatta-lucio-1851776618&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/overwatch-support-perk-mercy-kiriko-juno-zenyatta-lucio-1851776618">Read More</a></span></p></div></div></div>]]></content:encoded>
